Yes, there is an interesting symbolic parallel, with an important distinction.

The bifurcated sword most commonly associated with Ali ibn Abi Talib is known as Dhulfiqar (also spelled Zulfiqar or Dhu al-Fiqar). It is traditionally depicted with a split or forked tip, although historians debate whether the historical sword actually had that shape or whether the split became a later symbolic representation.

Across Islamic art and tradition, the split tip has accumulated many symbolic meanings, including:

* Justice and discernment.
* The ability to distinguish truth from falsehood.
* Courage guided by wisdom rather than brute force.
* The union of strength and moral responsibility.

